  "prompt": "At what point do a sperm cell and an egg become a boy or a girl?",
  "response": "The determination of whether a fertilized egg will develop into a boy or a girl is determined at the moment of **fertilization**.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Sex Chromosomes:** Human cells have 23 pairs of chromosomes, one pair of which are the sex chromosomes. These are X and Y chromosomes. Females have two X chromosomes (XX), and males have one X and one Y chromosome (XY).\n*   **Sperm's Role:** The egg cell always carries an X chromosome. The sperm cell, however, can carry either an X or a Y chromosome.\n*   **Fertilization:**\n    *   If a sperm carrying an X chromosome fertilizes the egg, the resulting zygote (fertilized egg) will have XX chromosomes, and the embryo will develop into a female.\n    *   If a sperm carrying a Y chromosome fertilizes the egg, the resulting zygote will have XY chromosomes, and the embryo will develop into a male.\n\nTherefore, the **specific sperm** that fertilizes the egg determines the sex of the offspring right at the beginning of development. This information is then present within the newly created zygote from the moment of fertilization.\n",
